  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the process to get a brand name trademarked in India?",
  "response": "The process to get a brand name trademarked in India involves several steps. Here is a comprehensive guide to help you through the process:\n\n### Step 1: Conduct a Trademark Search\n\nBefore filing an application, it's crucial to conduct a trademark search to ensure that the brand name you intend to use is unique and not already in use or registered by someone else. You can conduct this search on the Indian trademark registry website (ipindia.gov.in).\n\n### Step 2: Determine the Class of Goods or Services\n\nTrademarks are categorized into 45 different classes based on the type of goods or services they represent. Identify the appropriate class or classes for your brand name.\n\n### Step 3: File the Trademark Application\n\nTo file a trademark application, you can do it online through the Indian trademark registry website or hire a trademark attorney or agent to do it for you. You will need to provide the following details:\n- Applicant's name and address\n- Brand name and logo (if applicable)\n- Class of goods or services\n- Date of first use of the trademark in India (if applicable)\n- Power of Attorney (if filing through an attorney)\n\n### Step 4: Pay the Filing Fees\n\nThe filing fee varies based on the number of classes you are applying for. The fee structure is as follows:\n- For an individual, small enterprise, or startup: \u20b94,500 per class\n- For others: \u20b99,000 per class\n\n### Step 5: Examination of the Application\n\nOnce your application is filed, it will be examined by a trademark examiner. This process can take up to 18-24 months. The examiner will check if the trademark meets all the legal requirements and is not similar to existing trademarks.\n\n### Step 6: Publication in the Trademark Journal\n\nIf the examiner finds no issues, your trademark application will be published in the Trademark Journal, which is a weekly publication by the trademark registry. This publication allows third parties to oppose your trademark application if they believe it infringes on their rights. The opposition period lasts for four months from the date of publication.\n\n### Step 7: Respond to Oppositions (If Any)\n\nIf there is an opposition, you will have to respond to it within two months of receiving the notice. The opposition process can take several months to resolve.\n\n### Step 8: Registration\n\nIf there is no opposition, or if the opposition is resolved in your favor, your trademark will be registered. You will receive a registration certificate, and your trademark will be valid for ten years from the date of filing.\n\n### Step 9: Renewal\n\nYou must renew your trademark every ten years to keep it active. The renewal application should be filed within six months before the expiration of the registration.\n\n### Additional Tips:\n\n- **Hire a Trademark Attorney:** Although optional, hiring a trademark attorney can help navigate the complexities of the process and increase your chances of successful registration.\n- **Monitor Your Trademark:** After registration, keep an eye on the market to ensure no one else is using a similar trademark that could dilute your brand.\n\nBy following these steps and tips, you can successfully trademark your brand name in India.",
